just_use gesture_synth.py

# label: EARLY
# role: synthesize pointer-path telemetry for Python primitives
#       WHEN PYTHON HONESTLY KNOWS BOTH ENDPOINTS

The Elm client captures real mouse drags. Python primitives
don't come from mouse events, so a replay of a Python-driven
game wouldn't see any drag animation without synthesized
pointer paths.

This module builds those paths — but only for actions whose
endpoints Python actually knows in the **pinned viewport
frame** (shared with Elm via `BOARD_VIEWPORT_LEFT/TOP`).

## The rule (2026-04-21)

Python does NOT speculate about hand-card positions. Hand
layout is Elm's business, knowable only at replay time via
`LynRummy.HandLayout`. For hand-origin actions
(`merge_hand`, `place_hand`), `drag_endpoints` returns None
and Elm synthesizes at replay time.

Python DOES emit paths for intra-board actions where source
and target are pinned on both sides — `move_stack` and
`merge_stack` today. `split` waits on a target-loc policy (the
wire doesn't carry one).

This follows `feedback_record_facts_decide_later.md`: don't
put speculative coordinates on the wire.

## Surface

- `synthesize(start, end, samples)` — ease-in-ease-out path in
  viewport coords. Cosine ease on position, uniform time
  spacing; slow start, peak velocity at the midpoint, slow
  end. Duration = distance × `DRAG_MS_PER_PIXEL`.
- `drag_endpoints(prim, board_before)` — return `(start, end)`
  in viewport coords, or None if Python can't honestly supply
  them.
- `_stack_center`, `_stack_edge` — helpers shared by the
  move_stack / merge_stack branches. Source of "grab center of
  stack" and "drop on stack's left/right edge" points.

## Pointers

- Consumer: `auto_player.py` (attaches gesture_metadata only
  when `drag_endpoints` returns non-None).
- Complement: `telemetry.py` (read-side).
- Shared constants: `geometry.py` `BOARD_VIEWPORT_LEFT/TOP`
  must match Elm's `LynRummy.BoardGeometry.boardViewport{Left,Top}`.

## TODO

- `split` endpoints not yet emitted — the wire carries no
  target loc for Split, so synthesis needs either a wire
  extension or a deterministic "where the halves land"
  policy. Open question.
- `DRAG_MS_PER_PIXEL = 5` is a settled value, not a pending
  measurement — perceived replay pace reads well at this
  setting (Steve, 2026-04-21). Kept in sync with Elm's
  `dragMsPerPixel`.
